Create a JavaScript program that allows users to draw on an HTML5 canvas
model
```javascript
const canvas = document.getElementById('canvas');
const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

let isDrawing = false;
let x = 0;
let y = 0;

canvas.addEventListener('mousedown', (e) => {
  isDrawing = true;
  x = e.clientX;
  y = e.clientY;
});

canvas.addEventListener('mousemove', (e) => {
  if (isDrawing) {
    let dx = e.clientX - x;
    let dy = e.clientY - y;
    x = e.clientX;
    y = e.clientY;
    ctx.beginPath();
    ctx.moveTo(x - dx, y - dy);
    ctx.lineTo(x, y);
    ctx.stroke();
  }
});

canvas.addEventListener('mouseup', () => {
  isDrawing = false;
});
```

**HTML:**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <script src="script.js"></script>
  </head>

  <body>
    <canvas id="canvas"></canvas>
  </body>
</html>
```

**Instructions:**

1. Copy the above code into a JavaScript file named `script.js`.
2. Create an HTML file named `index.html`.
3. Copy the HTML code above into `index.html`.
4. Open `index.html` in a web browser.
5. Click and drag the mouse to draw on the canvas.

**Notes:**

* The `isDrawing` variable keeps track of whether the user is currently drawing.
* The `x` and `y` variables store the mouse position when the user starts drawing.
* The `ctx.beginPath()` method creates a new path on the canvas.
* The `ctx.moveTo()` method moves the cursor to the starting point of the path.
* The `ctx.lineTo()` method draws a line to the current mouse position.
* The `ctx.stroke()` method fills the path with the specified color.
* The `mouseup` event listener stops drawing when the mouse is released.

